            <div class="engArticle">
                <div class="article_txt">
<!--imgtbl_start_1--><div class="article_photo_center"   style="width:548px"><div class="article_photo"><!--imgsrc_start_1--><img alt=" Workers laid off from A, a sewing factory in Myanmar, take part in a demonstration in front of the factory last month. Courtesy of the labor union" src=http://img.khan.co.kr/news/2020/05/22/enkh_j1Tojs.jpg hspace=1 vspace=1 /><!--imgsrc_end_1--><p>Workers laid off from A, a sewing factory in Myanmar, take part in a demonstration in front of the factory last month. Courtesy of the labor union</p></div></div><!--imgtbl_end_1--><br />
<br />
A sewing factory in Myanmar run by a South Korean clothing company laid off all members of the factory’s labor union, retaining only the non-union workers, after the COVID-19 outbreak. Union members argued, “The South Korean employer suppressed the union using COVID-19 as an excuse,” and asked to be reinstated. South Korean companies reaped in benefits from Southeast Asia’s cheap labor and lax regulations, but some are not abiding by the region’s labor laws.<br />
<br />
According to the coverage by the Kyunghyang Shinmun on May 21, A, a sewing factory in Yangon, Myanmar fired 570 workers on March 28. Among them 520 were members of the labor union. “Orders have declined due to COVID-19” was the explanation the workers received from the company. The company continued to employ the remaining 700 workers. Last month, it suspended the operation of the factory for fifteen days and resumed operation early this month.<br />
<br />
The main office of the factory is B, a South Korean clothing company. B invested in and established the factory as a local corporation in Myanmar in early 2017. Since then, the factory has grown into an original equipment manufacturer (OEM) in Myanmar and has manufactured products for well-known fashion brands, such as ZARA and Mango.<br />
<br />
Maung Moe (27), the head of the labor union at A responded to an interview with the Kyunghyang Shinmun via e-mail and said, “The management wants the labor union to disappear. They are trying to get rid of demands for proper treatment as human beings. They are using COVID-19 as an excuse to kick us out.” Onma Myint(34), who was fired after working at the factory since May 2017, said, “I am angry at the fact that we were laid off unfairly and illegally. The workers are faced with immediate challenges in their livelihoods.”<br />
<br />
Union members launched a sit-in in front of the factory shortly after they were notified of their layoffs. They ended the demonstration on April 6, because the Myanmar government advised them to keep a physical (social) distance due to concerns of COVID-19. Moe said, “We will set up our stage for a protest in front of the company as soon as the government lifts the restriction on gatherings.”<br />
<br />
South Korean companies have built production factories in Southeast Asian countries to enjoy the benefits of cheap labor and lax regulations. Despite profits, some companies have been criticized for not abiding by the local labor laws and for neglecting their obligation to ensure labor rights by resorting to expedient measures. According to the labor union at A, some South Korean companies in Myanmar, the Philippines and Indonesia closed their factories for a certain period of time to get rid of the union and newly hired non-union workers.<br />
<br />
■ Company, “We received permission from the Myanmar government before laying off workers”<br />
<br />
They say companies often change the name of the factory or registrant to make it look like they are a different company. They then fire union members and hire new workers. The Myanmar labor law stipulates that an employer should not discriminate workers on the ground of race, religion, gender, age or affiliation with any particular group when employing workers.<br />
<br />
The Myanmar workers earn a petty wage. About 500,000 workers who work at clothing manufacturers in Myanmar earn US$3.5 (approximately 4,300 won) a day. The union at the factory A engaged in several strikes and raised their daily wages to $4.75 (approx. 5,530 won). Moe said, “The monthly rent for a one-room apartment located in the industrial areas in Myanmar is nearly $100 (approx. 123,030 won). Our wages still fall behind the living wage.”<br />
<br />
The union also notified ZARA and Mango of these facts. Reportedly, ZARA and Mango notified B that they would not sign further deals with the company unless it reinstated the twenty or so union members, who demand to be reinstated. B is waiting for a decision from an arbitration council at the Myanmar labor ministry.<br />
<br />
Moe said, “South Korean employers must respect the existence and rights of the labor union. We think South Korea is a country that protects law and human rights, but this company is the complete opposite. The more the company breaks the law, the more the Myanmar people will see South Korea in a negative light. We welcome South Korean employers, but we want them to treat us as human beings with rights, not animals.”<br />
<br />
A representative of B met with a Kyunghyang Shinmun reporter this day and claimed that the labor union’s argument was different from fact. The representative said, “The company did not specifically lay off union members. From what we know over a hundred union members are still working in the factory. The layoffs were determined based on job attitude and productivity. However, union members could have been absent from work more often due to strikes, so more union members may have been included in the list of layoffs.” He further explained, “We received permission from the Myanmar labor ministry before the layoffs. Orders have dropped due to COVID-19, so we had no choice but to reduce the number of workers. We also had to maintain a certain distance between workers to prevent the spread of COVID-19. Currently, we are in a tough situation, with orders dropping by 90% compared to last year.”<br/><br/><a href="http://news.khan.co.kr/kh_news/khan_art_view.html?artid=202005220600035&code=940100" target="_blank"><img src="http://img.khan.co.kr/spko/khan_eng/btn_eng_trans02.gif"></a>                </div>
            </div>

